    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:e533ca3c-9e4d-47fd-b18b-e118dcce1fd0",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 37-year-old Czech woman with a slim build and dark shoulder-length hair. She works as a secondary-school teacher in Brno and describes her daily routine as stressful, often skipping proper meals during the school day and eating a large dinner late in the evening. She lives with her partner and their two young children in a flat in the city centre. In her free time she enjoys hiking in the Moravian highlands, reading, and attending occasional yoga classes, though her exercise routine has become irregular over the past year.\n\n{patientName} presents with a several-month history of recurrent retrosternal burning that she describes as \"fire running down her chest every time she eats\" [PMID:9861914]. The burning sensation typically begins within 30 minutes of a meal and is partially relieved by drinking water [MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0]. She also reports frequent regurgitation of a sour, bitter fluid, particularly when she bends forward or lies down at night [PMID:9861914]. She wakes several nights per week with heartburn and has been self-managing with antacid tablets [MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0].\n\nShe additionally describes an intermittent dry cough that tends to worsen after meals [SNOMED:K21.9] and occasional precordial discomfort that she initially attributed to cardiac causes [SNOMED:K21.9]. She denies dysphagia, odynophagia, involuntary weight loss, or haematemesis — no alarm symptoms are present [PMID:9861914]. She admits to consuming spicy food frequently, drinks two to three cups of coffee per day, and uses one to two glasses of wine with dinner on most evenings [MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0].\n\n{patientName} is a non-smoker. She is close to her mother and sister, whom she sees regularly on weekends. She reports moderate work-related stress [MEDDIALOG:K21.9:0] and acknowledges that symptoms worsen significantly during busy teaching periods. She is sociable and enjoys cooking, though she has recently started avoiding certain trigger foods on the advice of a colleague who had similar complaints."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:00d722e9-134e-4fee-8e5c-d280bc6a1c31",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
